    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="1495"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1495">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.41/113.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Edwards</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Ciudad Juarez</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 24, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s telegram February 23. Have called upon authorities here relative to
                    the body of William Benton. All officials now at Juarez, being new men,
                    strangers to all border people, to take witness with me would not bring results.
                    They are afraid of the newspapers and the influence refugees and federal
                    sympathizers on American side. The said new officials seem anxious to assist in
                    the matter but say that Villa had taken with him to Chihauhua all his staff and
                    guards who were acquainted with the Benton affair but that they were confident
                    that the body had been buried as the law only admitted twenty-four hours before
                    interment. They promised that Villa would be immediately communicated with as to
                    the location of the grave. It is my opinion that the body was not embalmed and
                    that no undertaker attended but that the body was buried in a few hours after
                    death by the guards and during the later hours of the night. If Villa will allow
                    the soldiers who know the spot to give the information, I will request Zach Cobb
                    and others to accompany me to view the place and mark the same, if permission is
                    refused by Villa to disinter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edwards</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
